name: iprodione
source: Hughes LD; Palmer DS; Nigsch F and Mitchell JBO. 2008 Why are some properties more difficult to predict than others? A study of QSPR models of solubility; melting point and LogP. J. Chem. Inf. Model. 2008. 48 (1). pp 220?388
Reason: Iprodione is a dicarboximide fungicide with several functional groups that influence its melting point. Starting with a basic functional group, aniline (phenylamine), which has a melting point around 53°C. Adding two chlorine atoms to the aniline ring would typically increase the melting point by about 40°C, because halogens have high electronegativity and their presence stabilizes the lattice through stronger intermolecular forces, such as dipole-dipole interactions. The dicarboximide ring of iprodione, being a rigid and planar system, would contribute significantly to raising the melting point due to increased molecular symmetry and stronger intermolecular hydrogen bonding capabilities; this might increase the melting point by another 70°C. The two N-substituted groups attached to the dicarboximide would alter the melting point differently: the isopropyl group would slightly lower it due to increased entropy and steric hindrance, possibly by about -10°C, while the N-methyl group would have a minimal effect on the melting point, maybe changing it by about +5°C. Summing these individual effects gives us a predicted melting point.
Prediction: 53 (aniline base) + 40 (two chlorine atoms) + 70 (dicarboximide ring) - 10 (isopropyl group) + 5 (N-methyl group) = 158°C

For the dicarboximide moiety, this functional group adds restriction and planarity to the molecule, which leads to stronger intermolecular interactions and reduced molecular motion; we can estimate an increase of approximately 50°C due to this functional group. The isopropyl group, being bulky, introduces steric hindrance and increases the molecular size, which can slightly decrease the melting point due to more difficult packing; we estimate a decrease of 5°C for this effect. Lastly, the N-methyl substitution is small and may slightly increase the melting point due to added molecular weight and Van der Waals interactions; an estimated increase of 3°C can be assigned to this substitution. Based on these considerations, we can sum these effects to predict the melting point of iprodione.
Prediction: 53 (aniline base) + 40 (two chlorine atoms) + 50 (dicarboximide ring) - 5 (isopropyl group) + 3 (N-methyl group) = 141°C
